# Separate Unrelated Logic

Don't put everything in one giant `useEffect`. If you have multiple unrelated side effects, split them into separate `useEffect` calls.

This makes your code easier to understand and maintain.

```jsx
// ✅ Good: separate concerns
useEffect(() => {
  document.title = `You clicked ${count} times`;
}, [count]);

useEffect(() => {
  const subscription = subscribeToSomething();
  return () => subscription.unsubscribe();
}, []);
```

React guarantees that effects will run in the order they are written, and cleanup will run in reverse order.

slides.codeSnippet:
useEffect(() => {
  // Fetch user data
}, [userId]);

useEffect(() => {
  // Subscribe to user's online status
}, [userId]);

// Each effect deals with one thing.
